    "title": "Nick's Blog</title>\n  <link rel=\"preconnect\" href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com\">\n  <link rel=\"preconnect\" href=\"https://fonts.gstatic.com\" crossorigin>\n  <link href=\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&family=Space+Grotesk:wght@500;700&display=swap\" rel=\"stylesheet\">\n  <style>\n    :root {\n      --primary: #0F172A;\n      --accent: #F97316;\n      --bg: #FFFFFF;\n      --bg-alt: #F8FAFC;\n      --text: #1E293B;\n      --text-muted: #64748B;\n      --border: #E2E8F0;\n    }\n    * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }\n    body { font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif; color: var(--text); background: var(--bg); line-height: 1.7; }\n    h1, h2, h3 { font-family: 'Space Grotesk', sans-serif; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.3; }\n    .container { max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 24px; }\n    header { padding: 32px 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }\n    .logo { font-family: 'Space Grotesk', sans-serif; font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--primary); text-decoration: none; }\n    .back-link { display: inline-block; margin-bottom: 24px; color: var(--text-muted); text-decoration: none; font-size: 14px; }\n    .back-link:hover { color: var(--accent); }\n    .meta { font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 8px; }\n    h1 { font-size: 36px; margin-bottom: 16px; color: var(--primary); }\n    .subtitle { font-size: 18px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 32px; }\n    .tags { display: flex; gap: 8px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 32px; }\n    .tag { background: var(--bg-alt); padding: 4px 12px; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 12px; color: var(--text-muted); }\n    .content { font-size: 16px; }\n    .content h2 { font-size: 24px; margin: 40px 0 16px; color: var(--primary); }\n    .content h3 { font-size: 18px; margin: 24px 0 12px; color: var(--primary); }\n    .content p { margin-bottom: 16px; }\n    .content ul, .content ol { margin-bottom: 16px; padding-left: 24px; }\n    .content li { margin-bottom: 8px; }\n    .highlight { background: #FFF7ED; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; }\n    .key-insight { background: var(--bg-alt); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent); padding: 16px 20px; margin: 24px 0; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; }\n    .key-insight h3 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 16px; }\n    footer { padding: 40px 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); text-align: center; margin-top: 60px; }\n    footer p { font-size: 14px; color: var(--text-muted); }\n    @media (max-width: 768px) {\n      h1 { font-size: 28px; }\n    }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <header>\n    <div class=\"container\">\n      <a href=\"index.html\" class=\"logo\">Nick's Blog</a>\n    </div>\n  </header>\n  <div class=\"container\">\n    <article class=\"content\">\n      <p class=\"meta\">February 18, 2026 \u2022 Podcast Summary \u2022 ~12 min read</p>\n      <h1>The Most Effective Weight Training, Cardio & Nutrition for Women</h1>\n      <p class=\"subtitle\">Dr. Lauren Colenso-Semple breaks down the science of training and nutrition specifically for women.</p>\n      <div class=\"tags\">\n        <span class=\"tag\">Fitness</span>\n        <span class=\"tag\">Women</span>\n        <span class=\"tag\">Training</span>\n        <span class=\"tag\">Nutrition</span>\n        <span class=\"tag\">Huberman Lab</span>\n      </div>\n\n      <p>Dr. Lauren Colenso-Semple is an expert in the science of strength and muscle building and nutrition. In this episode of the Huberman Lab podcast, she explains the most effective resistance and cardiovascular training programs for women and whether and how those programs should differ from those followed by men.</p>\n\n      <div class=\"key-insight\">\n        <h3>\ud83c\udfaf The Bottom Line</h3>\n        <p>Women can build muscle effectively with similar protocols to men, but need to pay attention to hormonal fluctuations, nutrition timing, and progressive overload. The biggest myth? That women need radically different training programs.</p>\n      </div>\n\n      <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>\n\n      <h3>Repetition Ranges</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li><strong>6-12 reps</strong> \u2014 Optimal for hypertrophy (muscle growth)</li>\n        <li><strong>3-5 reps</strong> \u2014 Strength focused</li>\n        <li><strong>15-20 reps</strong> \u2014 Endurance/muscular endurance</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h3>Sets and Frequency</h3>\n      <p>For most women, <strong>10-20 sets per muscle group per week</strong> is the sweet spot. This can be broken into 2-3 sessions. Full-body workouts 2-3x per week are highly effective.</p>\n\n      <h2>Nutrition for Women</h2>\n\n      <h3>Protein</h3>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Aim for <strong>1.6-2.2g per kg</strong> of body weight daily</li>\n        <li>Protein timing matters less than total daily intake</li>\n        <li>Creatine monohydrate: <strong>3-5g daily</strong> \u2014 works equally well for women</li>\n      </ul>\n\n      <h2>Common Myths Debunked</h2>\n\n      <h3>\"Women will get too bulky\"</h3>\n      <p><span class=\"highlight\">False.</span> Women have 15-20x less testosterone than men, making it physiologically very difficult to build large muscles. Resistance training will make women stronger and more toned.</p>\n\n      <h2>Action Items</h2>\n\n      <div class=\"key-insight\">\n        <h3>\u2705 Start Today</h3>\n        <ol>\n          <li>Pick a strength program (full-body 2-3x/week)</li>\n          <li>Aim for 1.6-2.2g protein per kg bodyweight</li>\n          <li>Add 3-5g creatine daily</li>\n          <li>Be consistent for 12 weeks before judging results</li>\n        </ol>\n      </div>\n\n    </article>\n  </div>\n  <footer>\n    <div class=\"container\">\n      <p>Nick's Blog \u2014 Daily thoughts and learnings.</p>\n    </div>\n  </footer>\n</body>\n</html>",
